>>41834450
>Recognition
You're definitely better off self-publishing. My greatest hesitancy with a magazine deal is losing the distribution rights of a story I'm proud of to a magazine literally nobody reads, dooming the story to be read by tens of people at best. At least if you self publish you can direct people to a single, specific product to buy (rather than, say, a magazine they don't care about that happened to print your story), and you keep the rights to just leave your story the fuck online if you want.
>Money
Most of the places I've looked are offering pretty much an even grand for a story of Degeneracy's length, but I could have made many times that if I put the time I spent editing Degeneracy into actually working. Not that I regret it; just how it sorts out. As for individual sales, author/publisher percentages are only okay, and most small presses will probably command less social media marketing presence than you yourself do. Unless you're a well-recognized name you will almost certainly make more money self-publishing or pulling off a one-time sale to a magazine. This information is mostly hearsay as I haven't tried it both ways, but it seems to be the general wisdom

I'm taking you to task on Ripley
In the first movie, it's a stroke of brilliance making her a warrant officer. High enough to rank above some of the crew, but not enough to be as locked into WY's schemes/orders.
In Aliens, she loses everything initially: her job, her honor, and has to live with the fact she broke a promise to her now-dead daughter. Going back is originally a simple act of redemption from a woman's POV - if I can't have my life, then I can protect other families/mothers. Everything is framed in those terms, and the conflict becomes how badly does she want to regain her sense of femininity through Newt.
In Alien3, it goes further. She's lost everything again, and has to feel a connection to the prisoners. A guy could walk away and hole up best he could. Fat chance of that against the xenos. But Ripley is, and always has been, about family, blood or adopted.
Period, she's a mother. She protects the brood. In the first three movies, that is high up on the implied motivations. She doesn't have to help the Marines in Aliens survive. They are hers, and she does out of the most core traits of her personality - mother.

Ignoring that means you also missed the point of the alien reproduction/Queen/hive whatever that was a constant antagonistic element.

To be fair, I haven't seen all the media that Tigress is in.
